replies.text:
@DougWoodrow Short answer: ME-013 or 2-B. 

Long Answer: I needed to make a power adapter for my sister-in-law's cigarette lighter socket powered Mobicool. It took a lot of googling to find the power rating: 36W so 3A continuous. No brick wall socket adapter at the shops was rated this high so ATX power supply was the ticket. 12V 8A. Great. Built-in cooling fan and overload protection. BUT the measured voltage at full load dropped to 9.3V. Adding a CD-ROM drive to load the 5V and ensure the 12V gets regulated didn't work. So my secret weapon . . . except I forgot where I stashed it. Luckily a trip to the stationery shop fixed that. I don't know what the max wattage is but as long as it can cut Expanded Polystyrene, it is good enough for me. Between 1 and 2 Amps. You are on your own at higher currents. 

I expect you would have gotten this all sorted out years ago by borrowing a guitar or just buying all 6 strings and trying them out.
